INSERT INTO Paragraphs (ParagraphID, TopicID, Content) VALUES (4, 2, ' Polar Form In polar form, the vector is defined by its length and its direction as in Fig.~※. Therefore, we use the following descriptive notation sometimes: Some examples are shown in Fig.~※ where the direction is given in degrees.  Several complex numbers plotted in terms of length and direction of their vector representation. The angle is always measured with respect to the positive real axis; its units are usually radians, but are shown as degrees in this case. The angle is always measured from the positive -axis and may be either positive (counterclockwise) or negative (clockwise). However, we generally specify the principal value of the angle so that. This requires that integer multiples of be subtracted from or added to the angle until the result is between and. Thus the vector is the principal value of.');
