INSERT INTO Paragraphs (ParagraphID, TopicID, Content) VALUES (17, 6, 'Powers and Roots Integer powers of a complex number can be defined in the following manner: In other words, the rules of exponents still apply, so the angle is multiplied by and the magnitude is raised to the th power. Figure~※ shows a sequence of these: where the angle steps by a constant amount; in this case, exactly rad. The magnitude of is less than one, so the successive powers spiral in toward the origin. If, the points would spiral outward; if, all the powers would lie on the unit circle (a circle of radius 1). One famous identity is DeMoivres formula: The proof of this seemingly difficult trigonometric identity is actually trivial if we invoke Eulers formula for.  A sequence of powers for. Since, the vectors spiral in toward the origin. The angular change between successive powers is constant,.  Let,, and be three consecutive members of a sequence such as shown in Fig.~※. If and, plot the three numbers.');
