INSERT INTO Paragraphs (ParagraphID, TopicID, Content) VALUES (22, 10, 'Matrix Operations and Variables The basic variable type in MATLAB is a matrix. To declare a variable, simply assign it a value at the MATLAB prompt. For example,  >> M = [1 2 6; 5 2 1] M = 1 2 6 5 2 1 When the definition of a matrix involves a long formula or many entries, then a very long MATLAB command can be broken onto two (or more) lines by placing an ellipses ( ) at the end of the line to be continued. For example,  P = [ 1, 2, 4, 6, 8 ] +... [ pi, 4, exp(1), 0, -1 ] +... [ cos(0.1*pi), sin(pi/3),... tan(3), atan(2), sqrt(pi) ];  If an expression is followed by a semicolon (;), then the result is not echoed to the screen. This is very useful when dealing with large matrices. Also note that ; is used to separate rows in a matrix definition. Likewise, spaces or commas (,) are used to separate column entries. The size of the matrix can always be extracted with the size operator:  >> Msize = size(M) Msize = 2 3 Therefore, it becomes unnecessary to assign separate variables to track the number of rows and number of columns. Two special types of matrix variables are worthy of mention: scalars and vectors. A scalar is a matrix with only one element; its size is. A vector is a matrix that has only one row or one column. In the SP First laboratory exercises, signals will often be stored as vectors. Individual elements of a matrix variable may be accessed by giving the row index and the column index, for example:  >> M13 = M(1,3) M13 = 6 Submatrices may be accessed in a similar manner by using the colon operator as explained in Section ※.');
