INSERT INTO Paragraphs (ParagraphID, TopicID, Content) VALUES (85, 37, ' Demo: Spectrograms: Simple Sounds Synthesis of a Square Wave Using a simple MATLAB M-file, a synthesis was done via with a fundamental frequency of Hz, and. The fundamental period is secs. In Fig.~※, the plots are shown for three different cases where the number of terms in the sum is, 7, and 17. Notice how the period of the synthesized waveform is always the same, because it is determined by the fundamental frequency.  Summing harmonic components via : (top panel); (middle) and (bottom). The DC level of is included in each synthesis. The synthesis formula usually can be simplified to a cosine form. For the particular case of the square wave coefficients, when we take the DC plus first and third harmonic terms, we get the sum of two cosines plus the constant (DC) level given in equation  As more harmonic terms are added, a square-wave signal waveshape would be approximated better with this sum of cosines. However, notice what happens in Fig.~※ as increases; the sum of cosines appears to converge to the constant values and, but the convergence is not uniformly good–-the “ears” at the discontinuous steps never go away completely. This behavior, which occurs at any discontinuity of a waveform, is called the Gibbs phenomenon, and it is one of the interesting subtleties of Fourier theory that is extensively studied in advanced treatments.');
