INSERT INTO Paragraphs (ParagraphID, TopicID, Content) VALUES (113, 47, ' Four different pulses for D-to-C conversion. The sampling period is, i.e., Hz. Note that the duration of the pulses is one, two, or four times, or infinite for the ideal pulse. Zero-Order Hold Interpolation The simplest pulse shape that we might propose is a symmetric square pulse of the form This pulse is plotted in the upper left panel of Fig.~※. From Fig.~※, we see that the total width of the square pulse is ms and that its amplitude is 1. Therefore, each term in the sum will create a flat region of amplitude centered on. This is shown in the top part of Fig.~※, which shows the original 83 Hz cosine wave (solid gray line), its samples taken at a sampling rate of 200 samples/sec, and the individual shifted and scaled pulses, (dashed line). The sum of all the shifted and scaled pulses will be a “stairstep” waveform, as shown in the bottom panel of Fig.~※, where the gray curve is the original cosine wave, and the heavy orange curve shows the reconstructed waveform using the square pulse.');
