INSERT INTO Paragraphs (ParagraphID, TopicID, Content) VALUES (230, 96, 'The Linear-Phase Condition FIR systems that have symmetric filter coefficients (and, therefore, symmetric impulse responses) have frequency responses with linear phase. An example that we have already studied is the -point running sum, whose coefficients are all the same and therefore clearly satisfy the condition, for. The example of Section ※ also has linear phase because it satisfies the same symmetry condition. To see why linear phase results from this symmetry, let us consider a simple example where the system function is of the form Thus, and the length of the sequence is samples. After working out the frequency response for this special case, the generalization will be obvious. First, observe that we can write as If were greater, we would simply have more groups of factors of the form. Now when we substitute, each of these factors will become a cosine term, i.e., In our specific example, we have shown that is of the form where, in this case, and is the real function By following this style of analysis for the general case, it is easy to show that holds whenever, for. In the general case, it can be shown that the result depends on whether the integer is even or odd Equation shows that the frequency response of any symmetric filter has the form of a real amplitude function times a linear-phase factor. The latter factor, as we have seen in Section ※ on p.~, corresponds to a delay of samples. Thus, the analysis presented in Section ※ for the running-average filter is typical of what happens in the general symmetric FIR case. The main difference is that by choosing the filter coefficients carefully, as in Section ※, we can shape the function to have a much more selective frequency response.');
